<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-966-236  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 966 236.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 11 1989 n249 p47(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Is your computer system obsolete? (a look at the latestfads)(Final Word) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Delonas, Nick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The first question that needs to be answered when planning abusiness computer system upgrade is whether upgrading wouldprovide a financial payback.andP;  There is nothing wrong with finding'technologically obsolete' equipment perfectly adequate forspecific needs.andP;  Rapidly advancing technology has made renting asystem a popular option; it avoids the problem of buying the wrongequipment entirely.andP;  Information Systems managers should focus onfunctionally oriented proposals.andP;  Managers should demand thatvendors provide systems capable of complete integration with othersystems.andP;  Those planning to acquire a new computer system shouldspecify proprietary design independence as a goal, specifystandards used by several respected vendors, and make sure thesystem adheres to those standards before committing to buying it.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer SystemsObsolescenceEquipment AcquisitionBuy or Lease DecisionsCompatibilityMISPlanningHardware SelectionConnectivityUpgrading.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>